content:
@Zakhiggins there's some opinions that say keeping pro tools faders at or around zero is best because it gives the largest dynamic range for pro tools to work with when it does its summing. when doing the type of mixing that Jon, Teezio, etc do, you're dealing with stems where you're starting with everything coming up at zero anyway (you load up the stems, everything is at zero, and it sounds like the mix). so any adjustments you make to the sound in processing (compressors, saturators, eq, etc) aren't big gain changes anyway. so you just use the plugins's output control to compensate, thus keeping the faders around zero.

that's how I understand it, anyway. 

ps, i don't do this because I'm almost always mixing my own production sessions. it would be insane for me to try and completely rework everything to have faders at zero in one of my production sessions.

@Zakhiggins https://youtu.be/brXOrmgPCfE

These loudness videos are helpful for understanding the concept. But also, I don’t take my cue on how loud to make my mixes from any YouTuber/podcaster/plugin company/streaming platform. Cue into what your reference mixes sound like in tidal on hifi with normalization off. Route that into your DAW with a virtual output and you can compare LUFS on your favorite meters. The truth is there are no standards and trying to beat/cheat every loudness algorithm is folly. Make good shit that sounds like your favorite un-normalized records. 

Something else I have done, grab some CDs from a local library of your favorite records and put those wavs into a meter or RX and see what the pros are actually printing out loudness and peak wise.

@Eric Martin thanks for your reply man, re: clippers vs compression......yes i am familiar with that. I dont use compression for dynamics control either....you may have heard of the "clip to zero" strategy? i do a similar thing but then output my limiters/clippers at -6db instead of 0. Its similar to what johns doing just catching peaks and not squashing the life out of everythin....mike dean does it too IIRC. 

Re: spectral shaper : I didnt actually spot jon using his spectral shaper in that 1-6khz region, i saw it in the low mids....so having heard you and @oaklandmatt both mention it ...it seems hes defo already using this high mid scoop trick then! Ill still research the maths of the lufs algo because i like to really understand the psycho-acoustics and science of these sorts of things. Im after the ultimate mix in this life, lol .....i come from underground club music, where drums and bass and a sweet vocal are everything so its a constant balance/re-balance between lows/mids and highs as i learn more advanced techniques

..re: jons mix yesterday and clipping, and you mention clipping the attack portion of a sounds adsr , did you notice how much he uses transient shapers on almost everything? v clever. Personally, i love transients and fight hard to keep them and jons trick of putting a transient shaper after a clipper/limiter has been a revelation....(thanks @oaklandmatt , that gem came from your LWMR) .....bruce swedien said compression is for children, and i believe he evangelised about not killing transients ...i love a transient shaper and a clipper ....compressor , not so much.

This is something I’m still figuring out. I went through phases of not enough bass, too much bass, and now trying to find a balance. 

@Maxim mentioned how Manny’s Kendrick mixes don’t have too much going on at 40hz (I think this is the case on many of his mixes), but his basses or kicks sound HUGE. Not having too much lows and great balancing is probably what allows his mixes to have the loudness he does. 

While Jon’s philosophy is to save and cherish the low low subs, when you look at the meter, they’re not hitting like crazy amount. But I still feel that low low, which I also love.
